const faqs = [
  {
    q: "My Hardt rotisserie drive motor failed. Can it be repaired or replaced?",
    a: "Hardt drive motors are heavy-duty units designed for continuous spit rotation. When the motor fails (typically year 8 to 12 on Hardt Inferno or Sabre), replacement is the standard path. The motor is field-serviceable but bearings and gear-train wear together, partial repair fails again within months. OEM Hardt motor replacement runs $480 to $780. Worth it because Hardt rotisseries are $15,000 to $40,000 new.",
  },
  {
    q: "Do you service BKI DR-34 rotisseries?",
    a: "Yes. BKI DR-34 series is one of our common rotisserie service calls in LA delis and chicken specialists. Common service items: drive chain stretching (year 5 to 7), drive sprockets worn (paired replacement with chain), igniter and thermocouple on gas models, drip pan drain blockage from grease buildup. <a href=\"/brands/bki-rotisserie-repair/\">BKI rotisserie repair brand page</a>.",
  },
  {
    q: "Why does my rotisserie glass door keep cracking?",
    a: "High heat cycling (350 to 500°F operating range with rapid cooldowns when door is opened during service) thermal-stresses the tempered glass. Older Hardt and BKI doors used soda-lime tempered glass that fails at 6 to 10 years. Newer specs use borosilicate, which extends life. We replace with the manufacturer-spec replacement, not aftermarket (aftermarket glass with wrong thermal expansion coefficient fails again within months). $400 to $720 for door glass plus gasket replacement.",
  },
  {
    q: "How often does the drive chain need replacement?",
    a: "Year 5 to 7 typical on heavy-use rotisseries (chicken specialists running 100+ birds per day). Lower-volume operations (delis, occasional rotisserie) extend to year 10+. Always replace chain and sprockets together. New chain on worn sprockets fails again in months because the chain tracks into the worn sprocket profile. $260 to $480 paired set with labor.",
  },
  {
    q: "My rotisserie won't ignite. Gas or electric problem?",
    a: "Depends on the model. Gas rotisseries (most Hardt, BKI, Henny Penny rotisserie line, Hickory Industries): igniter and thermocouple are the usual culprits. Igniter pits and stops sparking, thermocouple weak and gas valve won't stay open. Electric rotisseries: heating element open-circuit or contactor failure. We diagnose with multimeter and gas pressure check. Repair $260 to $480 typical.",
  },
  {
    q: "Do you do annual maintenance on rotisseries?",
    a: "Yes. Annual contracts include drive motor amperage measurement, drive chain tension and wear inspection, drip pan and drain cleaning (grease buildup is the silent failure mode that ruins drains), igniter and thermocouple test on gas models, door gasket inspection, glass door inspection for thermal stress cracking. High-volume chicken specialists especially benefit from annual maintenance because failures cascade quickly when the equipment runs at capacity daily.",
  },
  {
    q: "What's your warranty?",
    a: "90 days SDAR labor warranty on every repair. Component manufacturer warranties (Hardt, BKI, Henny Penny, Hickory Industries) processed separately through the manufacturer's authorized network. BHGS Licensed #A49573. EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410). BBB A+ accredited.",
  },
];

